<div id="main_content">
	<h2>Author Kicks Off 'Age of India' Programs for Global Perspectives Office</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Shelly Yu
		
		<span class="date">Sept. 27, 2008</span></p>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:freeman@mail.ucf.edu">Mark Freeman</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-0935</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.ucfglobalperspectives.org">Global Perspectives Office</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>Author Mira Kamdar discussed water, energy, terrorism and other issues facing a rapidly expanding India and the global dimensions of those problems during her presentation at the University of Central Florida on Tuesday, Sept. 23.</p>
<p>The presentation entitled &ldquo;Risk and Reward in India&rsquo;s Booming Economy&rdquo; kicked off the Global Perspectives Office&rsquo;s 2008-2009 theme, &ldquo;The Age of India,&rdquo; and served as a feature event of <a href="index?page=article&amp;id=0024004144fcb4b10117ade51f2a0079d9">The India Program at UCF</a>, established in 2007. Supported by the Anil and Chitra Deshpande India Program Endowed Fund, the program aims to foster cultural understanding and cooperation between the United States and India through education.</p>
<p>A crowd of 225 students, faculty and community members attended Kamdar&rsquo;s presentation. She is a scholar of India and the award-winning author of &ldquo;Planet India: The Turbulent Rise of the Largest Democracy and the Future of our World.&rdquo; Her work has appeared in <i>The Times of India</i>, <i>Daily News &amp; Analysis</i>,&nbsp;<i>The International Herald Tribune</i>&nbsp;and many other publications around the world.</p>
<p>Kamdar said the issues facing India &ndash; including water, energy, terrorism, agriculture and political tensions caused by the growing gap between the rich and poor -- have impacts that extend well beyond the borders of India. The causes of those issues are global and are witnessed around the world, regardless of a nation&rsquo;s wealth. Kamdar proposes that the solutions to those problems also must be global and should be achieved through international diplomacy, cooperation and new, radical ideas that depart from tradition. In order to succeed, those solutions must be &ldquo;sustainable and equitable,&rdquo; Kamdar said.</p>
<p>Kamdar stressed the importance of U.S.-India relations, which are currently &ldquo;dominated by military concerns and big businesses.&rdquo; She said they should focus instead on the resolution of global issues. As democracies, the two nations have the potential to invent a new world. Kamdar stressed.</p>
<p>India possesses soft power, a growing cultural influence and a large young population that can be translated into a productive and cheap work force. Those qualities, combined with those of the United States, can help to formulate resolutions to issues. According to Kamdar, however, the only way to achieve this change is to mobilize citizens of both nations to put pressure on their respective governments. She explained, &ldquo;The concerns of the average American are the same as those of an average Indian.&rdquo;&nbsp; Those concerns revolve around the basic necessities of life and the improvement of the quality of life.</p>
<p>Since both countries are democratic, they must respond to the will of the people, Kamdar said. Once mobilized and empowered, people can effectively pressure their governments to respond to their needs. Kamdar left the audience with an optimistic view of the existence of a new world and encouraged everyone to do their part in achieving it.</p>
<p>Kamdar is the author of a memoir entitled &ldquo;Mobita&rsquo;s Tattoos: A Granddaughter&rsquo;s Journey from America into her Indian Family&rsquo;s Past.&rdquo; She also is a member of many international organizations, including the Pacific Council on International Policy and the Observer Research Foundation.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p>The event was sponsored by the UCF Global Perspectives Office, The India Program at UCF, The Anil and Chitra Deshpande Foundation, Lawrence J. Chastang and the Chastang Foundation, UCF Student Government Association, UCF College of Business Administration, UCF Political Science Department, UCF International Services Center, UCF LIFE and the Global Connections Foundation.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>UCF Stands For Opportunity:</strong> The University of Central Florida is a metropolitan research university that ranks as the 6th largest in the nation with more than 50,000 students. UCF's first classes were offered in 1968. The university offers impressive academic and research environments that power the region's economic development. UCF's culture of opportunity is driven by our diversity, Orlando environment, history of entrepreneurship and our youth, relevance and energy. For more information, visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
